04871nam a22007335i 9780813553467DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2011033053  a97808135534677 a10.36019/97808135534672doi  a(DE-B1597)529705  a(OCoLC)1156824412  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aNA5235.N63bR44 2012 4aNA5235.N63 7aARC0000002bisacsh04a726.609749/322231 aRegan, Brian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGothic Pride :bThe Story of Building a Great Cathedral in Newark /cBrian Regan. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b28 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Gothic Vision in Newark -- tPart II. Interludes -- tPart III. Sacred Heart Cathedral -- tPart IV. Completing Sacred Heart -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix A. The Cathedral’s Materials, Dimensions, and Plan -- tAppendix B. Chronology of the Newark Cathedral Project -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNewark’s Cathedral Basilica of the Sacred Heart is one of the United States’ greatest cathedrals and most exceptional Gothic Revival buildings. Rising from Newark’s highest ground and visible for miles, it spectacularly evokes its historic models. Gothic Pride sets Sacred Heart in the context of American cathedral building and, blending diverse fields, accounts for the complex circumstances that produced it. Calling upon a wealth of primary sources, Brian Regan describes in a compelling narrative the cathedral’s almost century-long history. He traces the project to its origins in the late 1850s and the great expectations held by the project’s prime movers—all passionate about Gothic architecture and immensely proud of Newark—that never wavered despite numerous setbacks and challenges. Construction did not begin until 1898 and, when completed in 1954, the cathedral became New Jersey’s largest church—and the most expensive Catholic church ever built in America. During Pope John Paul II’s visit to the United States in 1995, he celebrated evening prayer at the Cathedral. On that occasion, the Cathedral of the Sacred Heart was elevated to a basilica to become the Cathedral Basilica of the Sacred Heart. Meticulously researched, Gothic Pride brings to life the people who built, contributed to, and worshipped in Sacred Heart, recalling such remarkable personalities as George Hobart Doane, Jeremiah O’Rourke, Gonippo Raggi, and Archbishop Thomas Walsh. In many ways, the cathedral’s story is a lens that lets us look at the history of Newark itself—its rise as an industrial city and its urban culture in the nineteenth century; its transformation in the twentieth century; its immigrants and the profound effects of their cultures, especially their religion, on American life; and the power of architecture to serve as a symbol of community values and pride.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBasilicaszNew JerseyzNewark. 0aGothic revival (Architecture)zNew JerseyzNewark. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355346740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813553467423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813553467.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_S